POLICY AND MARKET TREND UNDER COVID-19
1. Introduction
1.1 Background: Outbreak of Coronavirus
On March 11, WHO declared the global outbreak a pandemic. The coronavirus outbreak, which began in
Wuhan, China, at the beginning of December 2019. Now it has spread to more than 200 countries and the
cumulative cases are still sharply increasing. The majority of cases are in USA and European countries
like Italy, Spain, and Germany. The world is still finding a cure for this new coronavirus. Many people are
afraid there is a new financial crisis since 2008 because of the outbreak of coronavirus.
(Source: Statista (6 April 2020): https://www.statista.com/)
1.2 The fallout from the coronavirus outbreak
However, coronavirus is not only a global health issue, it affects the global economy and financial market.
At the beginning of the coronavirus outbreak, many factories in China had to shut down temporarily.
There are many companies that rely heavily on factories in China for parts and materials, the shutdown of
factories will deeply affect the supply chain. Also, several sectors have been hit hard like airlines, hotels,
retail because most people try to not be exposed to crowds and many governments announced travel
suspension and restrictions in operations of private businesses, including retail stores, nightclubs, hotels
and malls. Some companies may not be able to survive or suffer a great loss during the outbreak. It
increases the default risk of investment-grade bonds, they may be downgraded to junk bonds. Not only
the bond market is affected, the index and stock price around the world fluctuate a lot. One of the reasons
is that investors feel panic about the current situation and may panic sell their investment.
1.3 The Federal Reserve reaction to coronavirus
To make things better, the Federal Reserve announced an emergency rate reduction on March 3, cutting
its policy rate 50 basis points to 1-1.25 percent. From the diagram, we can see it is the first unscheduled,
emergency rate cut since the financial crisis in 2008. The purposes of this emergency rate cut are
preventing economic recession and stimulating the economy.
(Source: CNBC(13 March 2020 ) : www.cnbc.com)
1.4 Federal Reserve expectation after rate cuts
In theory, after the rate cut, the commercial banks will lower their interest rate, more people and firms will
borrow from banks because they can pay less interest. It can keep firms in business and people in jobs.
Also, stimulating consumption and investment. Finally, it can reach the purpose of stabilizing the
financial system or economy.
1.5 How do the experts think about rate cuts?
Many experts in the financial market questioned the limits of monetary policy in responding to a global
health crisis. For example, the founder of London-based investment group Algebris, Davide Serra said “If
you want to fix your health by going to a bank, you’ve got a problem. The pandemic risk is real, it is
serious. Who is in charge here is the WHO, not the central banks.” and the strategist at Principal Global
Investors, Seema Shah said “Certainly, rate cuts will not help restock emptying grocery shelves. Monetary
policy is hopeless when supply simply cannot feed demand.” It shows that many experts don’t believe
monetary policy like rate cuts can save the market.
2. Policy outlook
2.1 What the US government has done
On 11 March, US President Donald Trump announced that his administration will provide a $50 billion
relief package to small business owners affected by the coronavirus outbreak as part of sweeping efforts
to hinder the economic impact of the growing pandemic. Low-interest loans are one of the several
initiatives to reassure businesses after days of market volatility. The US president said that he will take
executive action to provide emergency paid sick leave for workers who are ill and under quarantined. He
also called for deferments on tax payments for businesses and individuals affected by coronavirus without
interest or penalties, as well as immediate payroll tax relief for U.S. companies.
The most significant policy is the 30-day ban on all travel to and from Europe, in order to slow the virus'
spread. This led to a horrible day on the stock market, as the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 10
percent, or more than 2300 points in a single day. That is the biggest daily drop since the stock market
crashed in 1987, on what came to be known as Black Monday. The decline has Triggered trade circuit
breaker for the second time in a week, which is unprecedented. This has left the stock market in the
United States firmly in a bear market.
(Source: Dow Jones Index (12 March 2020): www.finance.yahoo.com)
2.2 What the Federal Reserve has done
Economists originally expected the Federal Reserve to further cut the interest rate by 50 basis points when
policy makers gather on March 18 and again at their April 29 meeting due to Fear of the coronavirus’
damage to the economy. They expected a record low of 0% to 0.25% rate which was last seen in 2015.
However, it turned out that the Federal Reserve did not even wait until the March 18
th
meeting. Instead,
the Federal Reserve took an emergency action to Directly cut 100 basis points of the interest rate to a 0%
to 0.25% rate on Sunday, 15
th
of March. The action suggested the Federal Reserve was concerned that
waiting even three more days could be too late to prop up the economy, and they felt the financial markets
are at significant risk.
(Source: Federal Reserve (2016-2020): https://edition.cnn.com)
In addition, the federal reserve also announced the launch of a massive $700 billion quantitative easing
program to shelter the economy from the effects of the virus. The program will take the form of $500
billion of Treasuries and $200 billion of agency-backed mortgage securities. The bond and mortgage
security purchases are tools the Federal reserve previously used during the most recent recession in 2008.
2.3 Reaction of other countries
This table has summarized the policy rate cut among several countries. We can see, Australia and
Malaysia cut their interest rate by 25 bp, on the same day that the US government announced its rate cut.
One day later, our city Hong Kong announced a 50 bp rate cut. On 5
th
March, Canada had its 1
st
rate
reduction by 50 bp, and 9 days later, it cut its interest rate again by 50 bp. On 11
th
March, Bank of England
cut its policy rate by 50 bp. Noted that it is its 1
st
rate reduction since August 2018. Besides this, Norway,
Vietnam, South Korea and other countries have had their rate cut and other monetary policies as well, but
we will not discuss in detail here.
From the previous table, it is noticed that Canada has two interest rate reductions within 9 days. Also, the
Federal Reserve has two rate cuts within two weeks as well. It is doubted whether the 1st rate cut is
ineffective, or the rate cut itself is ineffective at all. In the later part of this report, we will discuss the
effectiveness of this monetary policy in detail.
It is also worth mentioning the reaction of European Central Bank (ECB). Some economists expected it to
have a 10 bp rate cut after 3
rd
March, but the ECB did not cut its rate further negatively at that time.
Instead, it adopted Quantitative easing policies, including supporting bank lending and increasing its asset
purchase program by 120 billion euros. The ECB would expand its purchase on private sector bonds and
allow the banking system to enjoy even more liquidity by offering more favourable terms. This
encourages banks to borrow money from the central bank and lend it to businesses and people, thus, it
boosts lending. The ECB has already played its role to adopt monetary policy in 19 European economies,
and it is the time for each country to decide its fiscal policy.
(Source: CNBC (12 March 2020): www.cnbc.com )
2.4 Prediction of the world market in the future
After having a look in other countries’ policy, we will have a brief prediction of the world market.
(Source: China Briefing (3 April 2020): www.china-briefing.com)
Although the condition in China seems to be under control, fewer new confirmed infections and new
deaths are reported, damage by the coronavirus cannot be clearly evaluated, it is unlikely Beijing would
launch any large-scale monetary policies. Furthermore, according to Reuters, the Chinese government is
planning to invest up to RMD 2.8 trillion to spur its infrastructure, developing “new infrastructure”,
including big data centers, 5G infrastructure, and facilities for new energy vehicles and the like. Thus, it is
expected that China may transit from a polluting, export-led manufacturing economy to a high-tech and
service-driven economy in the future.
(Source: China Briefing (6 April 2020): www.china-briefing.com )
From the previous part, we can see the policy announced by the Federal Reserve did not help much to
reassure the U.S. market. Even Fed Chair Jerome Powell agreed that rate cuts could not fix the chaotic
condition. When it comes to the ECB, on 18
th
March, they announced a new Pandemic Emergency
Purchase Programme, spending extra 750 billion euros, offering an interest rate at -0.75% and other
policies. However, after a decade of monetary policy, some economists doubted that whether its QE
policy would be significantly influential. If conditions become worse, many economists say the politicians
should work with their central banks in order to have a better budget planning, or else the world market
may be driven toward zero rates in the future.
(Source: European Central Bank: www.ecb.europa.eu ; Los Angeles Times (15 March 2020):
www.latimes.com)
3. Trend and Liquidity Trap
3.1 2020 stock market crash vs 2007-2008 financial crisis
When the US Federal Reserve cut the interest rates for the first time this year on March 3, there was a
sense of familiar unease among investors: the emergency rate cut, the plunging stock market and the
widening shadow of recession evoked their memory of the crisis in 2008.
It is natural to compare the situation nowadays with that of 2008 and get some hint from the subprime
crisis. People should be aware that this time is different: firstly, the direct cause of the crisis in 2008 was
the accumulation of subprime mortgages, which was a long term factor; while the covid-19 is a relatively
short-term one. Although the situation is getting worse, it seems impossible to predict when the epidemic
will come to an end, the Chinese expert Zhong Nanshan claimed on March 12 that if all countries respond
to WHO's call for more intervention at the national level, it can be expected that the outbreak will be
under control in June.
Secondly, before the crisis in 2008, the economy was in great recession: the house price started to fall in
2006 (at that time, the Federal Reserve and analysts welcomed it as a slowdown in the overheated market,
however, it was a trigger event bursting the housing bubbles). Nevertheless, before 2020, there has been a
10-year bull market. See the S&P 500 index plot below, the US stock market has been on an
unprecedented streak since 2009.
Last but not the least, today's market risk control ability is stronger than before. After the subprime crisis,
the government and investors are more alert and experienced.
(Source: S&P 500 (2008-2020): www.macrotrends.com)
3.2 Hints from the 2008 subprime crisis
Although these differences remain, the Federal Reserve's rate cut in 2007-2008 is helpful for us to have a
feeling why the rate cut in the early March (as well as the one on March 19) was not that effective.
Here is the rate cut time table in 2007-2008:

There were 10 times cut from September 2007 to December 2008, starting from 4.75%, the rate finally
became 0.25%. There is a warning message, before the first rate cut in 2007, the Federal interest rate was
5.25%. However, before the rate cut this year on March 3, the base rate was only 1.5%, indicating that the
times that the interest rate can be reduced is much less than before. The president Jerome Powell
announced on March 16 that the Federal Reserve is unlikely to implement negative interest rates as the
next step to save the economy. Therefore, after the second emergency rate cut on March 19, there is little
chance for the US to cut the rate again.
Further see the Dow Jones Index from 2007-2008, it can be seen that it is not unusual that rate cut strategy
doesn't work.
(Source: Dow Jones Index (2007-2008): www.finance.yahoo.com)
The orange lines added on the plot show the time when the rate cuts were done. It seems that actually
none of the 10 cuts really saved the collapsed trend. There were some slight rises, however, they were at
most short-term oversold rebound and did not save the market. It shows that the failure of the rate cut
strategy in March 2020 is not the first one, it happened before and may also happen in the future.
3.3 The bomb of the balloon —— quantitative easing and liquidity trap
After the subprime crisis, US and other European and American countries expanded the economy
continuously using quantitative easing and other easing strategies, including buying large-scale
government bonds, expanding balance sheets and rate cuts.
In the past 11 years, the US never stopped its step to make the economy balloon larger and larger: the
treasury bonds have tripled from $7 trillion in 2007 to $23 trillion now. Although in 2015, the US Federal
Reserve started to conduct the balance sheet reserve, this action was soon over, completely ending in
2018. In 2019, the Federal Reserve cut interest rate three times continuously and expanded the balance
sheet with a breath-taking speed. In European countries, the national debt also increased rapidly.
Moreover, the ECB has entered the era of negative interest rates since 2014. It indicates that many
developed countries in Europe and America have applied quantitative easing to the extreme —— the
balloon was full of air, and there is a risk of explosion at any time.
3.3.1 The diminishing marginal effect of quantitative easing
Covid-19 might be the needle to burst the huge balloon, but the true murderer behind it is the liquidity
trap. Initially, the effect of quantitative easing can be good, but over time, the marginal effect became
weaker and weaker —— the liquidity was trapped.
To show and explain the decreasing marginal effect, we can see the performance of S&P 500 and CRB
from 2009 to 2012. In this period, the Federal Reserve launched four large-scale quantitative easing.
There are two points worth noting: first, after each quantitative easing, the stock price goes up less than
the previous one. After the first QE action (from Nov 2008 to April 2010), the market rose by 50%, but
after the following actions, the market only rose by 26%, 21% and 7% separately. It is similar to doping in
sports, for the first time the result might be greatly improved, but next, if the measurement of stimulants
remains unchanged, the effect of improving would decrease.
The second point is, during the first and second QE, CRB and stocks rose simultaneously, but in the third
and fourth stage, the commodity price did not keep up, indicating that the market did not follow the
expected effect of QE.
(Source: S&P 500 vs CRB (2009-2012): http://www.woodsfordcapital.com)
Also, checking the inflation rate and velocity of circulation in the US. From 2014 to 2017, the inflation
rate is not up to 2% as expected by the central bank, there was even the possibility of deflation. More
importantly, the circulation rate declined every year, which indicates that the huge sum of money put in
by the central bank was not invested into the real economy, but still stored “safely” in the bank.
(Source: US Inflation Rate (2010-2020): http://www.tradingeconomics.com)
(Source: Velocity of M2 Money Stock (2008-2019): http://www.fred.stlouisfed.org.com)
The major reason why the decreasing marginal effect indicated by the American economist Steven
Pressman is that: though the economy has experienced a decade of rapid growth since 2009, the gap
between the rich and the poor has further increased. The average income of the first 1% of the rich in the
US grew by more than 60%, while the US economy grew at an average annual rate for only 2.3%, and the
growth rate of other Americans was less than 5%.
Thereby, the problem of allocation is an indisputable fact. The continuous expansion of the gap would
reduce the consumption capacity of the majority of American people, resulting in weak demand and slow
economic growth. If the situation of unfair allocation could not be eased, the economy would still fall into
a long recession and the liquidity would be trapped.
No matter how the monetary policy eased in these countries, the economy can hardly be stimulated
effectively. That can be the reason why the effect of the rate cuts on March 3 and March 19 was really
weak and only lasted for a short time. On March 23, the Federal Reserve announced the start of a new
round of quantitative easing, claiming US treasury bonds and MBS bonds would be bought back
indefinitely. However, if the liquidity is already in the trap, it is foreseeable that the market will hard to be
improved.
3.3.2 The evidence of the US falling into the liquidity trap
The term "liquidity trap" was created by Keynes, describing a situation where the interest rates are low
while the saving rates are high. It seems that it is the situation that the US is facing now. People's
willingness to invest is not high, under the influence of the increasingly severe epidemic, the situation
may be even worse.
(Source: US Saving Rate (2015-2020): www.statista.com)
We may get more hints from the treasuries yield, which could be seen as the gauge of investors' anxiety.
In the early March, the yield of 10-year treasury bonds fell below 1% for the first time in history. What's
more, on March 25, the yields of 1-month and 3-month bonds all became negative.
(Source: Treasury Rate (2 March 2020): www.statista.com)
The low treasuries yield indicates that a large amount of hedge funds poured into the treasuries market:
many investors seeking the safety of it. It means that people have money, but their willingness to invest in
stock decreased a lot. The epidemic and the result of the liquidity trap severely undermined confidence in
financial markets, the warning signs have appeared.
4. Problems & Consequences
4.1 Increasing amounts of leveraged finance
Leveraged finance is made up of leveraged loans and high-yield bonds for non-investment-grade firms
that are highly indebted and often owned by private equity. According to the historic data, leveraged
finance has doubled since the global crisis in 2008. Moreover, the share of leveraged loans is consistently
increasing, just as immediately before the global crisis.
(Source:BIS(2018) https://www.weforum.org)
Increasing amounts of financing and loosening of standards are both signals of a boom with strong
competition and overtrading. Debt financing with thin equity stakes is risky especially when the market is
unstable. If the economy turns, equity is quickly rushing to failure.
After coronavirus, in the search for yield in the current low-interest environment, both banks and
investment funds are driving the leveraged finance market, turning to riskier investment strategies to
obtain higher returns and plug growing deficits.
4.2 Corporate bond downgrade
4.2.1 Causes-Lax financial conditions results in the downward rating
Years of extremely lax financial conditions have encouraged and enabled massive issuance of debt at
ever-lower interest rates, including tighter spreads over risk- free government securities.
The result is that corporate debt has risen significantly faster than earnings growth and cash balances,
resulting in a significant downward ratings migration that now has half of the total investment-grade
market clinging to that status with a triple B rating, up from less than one-fifth in 2001. Among the
companies on that bottom rung, a third are already rated triple B minus, and thus at greater risk of a
downgrade to junk.
The more the virus spreads, the effects of shocking demand, supply and finance are severer especially for
those companies operating in disrupted areas such as Wuhan province in China and Northern Italy, and in
disrupted sectors like airlines, hotels, and even energy. More and more companies report supply chain
problems.
4.2.2 Situations — The outlook was getting cloudy for corporate credit heading into the
coronavirus scare
(1) Deterioration of financial market nowadays
Nowadays, the situation of the financial market is really not optimistic. European and American stock
markets have plummeted, S & P 500 index futures and Nasdaq futures have triggered trading restrictions
before the market. Major European stock indexes have plummeted by more than 7%, Asia-Pacific shares
have fallen to the meltdown, and America shares have three times meltdown, the MSCI Global Index is
bound to fall into a bear market. High grade government bond yields, which move inversely to prices,
have steadily dropped. Ten-year US Treasuries yield about 0.9%, a record low, compared with about 2.7%
a year ago. Investors are agreeing to lose money by owning similar-maturity German and Swiss
government bonds, which yield -0.5% and -0.8% respectively.
The slash of individual stocks caused panic among investors, severely affecting business activities and
investment willingness. Traders are selling anything they think is risky as Covid-19 and rush into safety.
(2) Multiple corporations were hit with corporate debt downgrades
Coronavirus has shut down dining rooms, bars, flights, sporting events, and even the city of the world,
causing huge financial difficulties for companies in many industries. As a result, there are many
corporations facing the problem of downgrades.
For example, ExxonMobil, the nation’s biggest oil and gas company, whose credit has long been regarded
as the gold standard, suffered downgrade in March. With commodities prices especially oil plunging,
Standard & Poor’s Global Ratings downgraded ExxonMobil’s issuer credit rating and unsecured debt
rating to AA from AA+. The rating agency stated that ExxonMobil’s cash flow and leverage measures fell
well below its expectations and maintained a negative trend, warning the oil behemoth had not taken
adequate steps to improve cash flow. Also, as the analyst’s writing, there is potential for a further
downgrade if the company cannot take effient measures to improve the situation over the next 12 to 24
months.
Boeing, the world's largest aerospace company, also encountered difficulties. On 24 Mar, Fitch ratings
downgraded Boeing’s long term ratings by two notches to BBB from A-, only one step away from junk
territory. Since the coronavirus dramatically influenced the airline traffic and financial results, under this
scenario, Fitch does not expect Boeing could rebuild its credit, which has been mired in problems
associated with the grounding of its 737 Max aircraft. According to JP Morgan’s prediction, Boeing is
poised to burn through $5 billion in 2020. At the same time, it is reported that Boeing is requesting
short-term financial help for itself and its suppliers from the federal government . “Boeing’s cash flows
for the next two years are going to be much weaker than we had expected, due to the 737 Max grounding,
resulting in worse credit ratios than we had forecast,” S&P said. “The significant reduction in global air
travel due to the coronavirus will likely result in an increase in aircraft order deferrals, further pressuring
cash flows.”
4.2.3 Consequence — corporate bond downgrades worsen the outlook of financial market
Corporate bond investors prefer big spreads, which means that choosing the less desirable credit qualities
would be compensated by high yield for the risk taking on companies. However, the prediction of Fitch’s
rating case includes a significant global economic downturn in 2020, especially the second quarter. There
is a great possibility that the economy will go into a mild recession, experiencing a higher default rate.
Hence, for the investors and regulators, one of the biggest worries is the massive build up of corporate
debt. According to the alarm of regulators’ report in the US and Europe, there are more than $3 trillion in
leveraged loans which are junk bonds and loans that have a higher risk of default.
The outlook was getting cloudy for corporate credit because of the coronavirus. Beverages, medical
products and devices, midstream suppliers and refining and marketing were the only 4 of the 53 sectors
which had positive outlooks according to Moody’s analyzes with 15 negative, which is the worst
prediction since the financial crisis.

5. Conclusion
(Source: Johns Hopkins https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com)
In conclusion, as the number of coronavirus cases is still growing rapidly, the situation is not optimistic.
Kristalina Georgieve, the IMF’s managing director, stated that the global economic slowdown caused by
the coronavirus will be more severe than previously predicted. Growth in 2020 would slump to the
estimated global growth of 2.9%, compared with the prior forecast of 3.3%. The US economy is expected
to contract in the second quarter of 2020. More than 8 countries will fall into a severe recession.
Now, it is really the time for us to prepare for the coming global financial crisis.
